Updating based on a slightly more careful look at daily average doses administered. Pace of doses delivered would need to increase by about 24% (to ~2.0M/day) in the last week (3/25-3/13) to get above the 105M threshold. That seems like a big jump without any big changes (e.g., in supply of J&J in the last week). Even if there was a big increase in supply, the ability of states to increase numbers with the new supply is probably limited and would ramp up steadily.

Earlier, I overestimated how quickly vaccination would pick up. It's just been increasing pretty steadily. Right now, the CDC website says we're at 95.0M. Over the next few days, I estimate there will be about 9M to 10M (maybe closer to 9.1M) more vaccinations. So total for this period will be 95.0M + ~0.5M (J&J) + ~9M*0.65(Pfizer/Moderna, additional people w/ at least one dose) = 101.35M Additional check from another angle: we were at 82.8M 7 days ago, March 22 => 12.2M added in 7 days => 1.74M added/day; let's say essentially 3 more days of reporting will contribute to the total through March 31; 1.74M/day * 3 days = 5.22M. But, vaccinations/day have been increasing slightly, so we'll get to a total a bit higher than that. Luckily, 101M is at the low end of the bin. We might end up a bit higher, but I don't think we can end up below 100M or above 105M at this point.

At the moment around 93,600,000 people have received at least one dose of the covid vaccine and on average 2.71 million covid vaccines are administered per day. Given that there are a few days left and the increasing rates of vaccination, it is possible that the number will exceed 100,000,000 but it also may not. (all numbers come from the CDC covid data tracker)

If daily average remains between 1.5 mil and 1.6 mil people receiving a dose (where it's been for a couple of weeks), based on total as of 3/25 that puts it between 101 mil and 103 mil total. With a couple of states opening eligibility to all adults on Monday 3/29, it seems more likely that the number of people receiving a dose could tick up slightly than go down. But the daily rate would have to go up to about 2.1 mil per day over the last six days (3/26-3/31). That's a pretty big jump, so I'm not very optimistic. (Pls flag if the numbers/math are obviously wrong!) Potential for a drop in the rate could be weather related (e.g., flooding in Nashville), but it doesn't seem like there are big weather problems on the horizon over the next three days. The daily rate would have to go down to about 1.28 mil over the last 6 days; again, that seems like a pretty big change, so I'm keeping both the upper and lower bounds at low probabilities.

Update. I suspect we will probably be at about 98M who have received at least one dose by end of March 31. Then, a few days of filling in the gaps. It doesn't seem likely that there would be more than 7M people added after March 31 as data comes in. That would correspond to about 10M more vaccinations administered. I don't think that many are likely to be added to the tally for vaccinations up to March 31 over the week up to April 7.

Estimating that if this week's vaccination rate picks up 1.14x faster than last week's weekday average (1.14x is a figure I derived from speeding YouTube videos up to a speaking rate which I think could represent the sense of acceleration for working faster with the vaccines), while adding the average weekly growth to today's value in order to get Monday's starting point, it still does not reach 100M.

Updating. Right now, we're at 93.6M. And when you look at the graphs ("Daily Count" at https://covid.cdc.gov/covid-data-tracker/#vaccination-trends), it's not clear that by April 7, we'll hit enough to get >105M with at least 1 vaccine. Maybe we'll add up to 1M J&J, and maybe 11M or 12M Pfizer/Moderna; multiply P/M by ~0.65 (calculated from data) to get the number of people with at least one dose = ~7.5M. So unless we drastically increase vaccination rates, it's looking unlikely that we'll get above 105M. We'll probably end up at around 102M to 103M. But, the brackets are pretty narrow....

Currently, the CDC's count of persons receiving at least one dose is: 93,631,163 people. The last day for solidly reported data (not still updating upward) from the CDC is 23 Mar with 88,548,411 people. The current seven day moving average for the last three weeks for new vaccine doses has been approximately 1.55M -1.59M per day. If we assume that the 7 day moving average for at least one doses administered is lower than the actual at 1.5M from the period from 23 Mar to 31 Mar then we would have 88.5M + 1.5M * 8 = 100.5M. If we instead use 26 Mar data which is still being revised upward of 93,537,500 we would get 93.5M + 1.5*5 = 101M. Both are over 100M. It seems very likely that this will make the 100M mark but miss the 105M mark.

According to the CDC, as of 3/22/21, 82.8M people in the US have received at least one dose of a COVID-19 vaccine (https://covid.cdc.gov/covid-data-tracker/#vaccinations). Assuming a reporting lag of at most 1 week, the 7-day moving average of doses administered/day was at about 1.55M/day a week ago. It has generally been going up, as more doses become available. I can extrapolate the CDC vaccine administration curves to ~1.8M vaccines/day average for last week, ~2.1M vaccines/day average for the coming week, and ~2.4M vaccines/day for March 29-31, all with giant error bars that make these predictions difficult. Then total additional vaccines given by March 31 to be reported by April 7, 2021 = approx. (0.25M * 7) + (2.1M * 7) + (2.4M * 3) = ~23.7M more vaccines.

I did an integral under the curve of daily shots to forecast a quadratic function of cumulative shots of 147.7M shots by 3/31. That is 54.0M more shots than on 3/9. There are 28.9M people who have received a single dose. I assumed 80% of those people will get a second shot in the next 21 days (3 weeks for Pfizer, 4 weeks for Moderna, no second shot for J&J). That implies 30.9M new people getting shots by end of March to get to 147.7total jabs. That means 61.1M+30.9M = 90.1M people with at least one shot. I put a 10% standard deviation on the incremental 29.0M people to receive a first shot. Then I just took the percentages from a CDF of a normal distribution function based on total people with at least one dose.

Just a simple extrapolation suggests we would land around 100m. Given the increasing accessibility, it's tempting to use a more aggressive linear growth assumption. As of 5 March 2021, there were 55,547,697 people in the United States who received at least one dose of the COVID-19 vaccine. The current seven day running average for new people to receive at least a single COVID-19 vaccine dose is 1,194,785, showing a steady upward trend since 23 February 2021. In the past seven days, the trend has shown an average increase of 64,422.45 people over the past seven days. At the current rate of this trend, there would be 88,287,102 people having received at least one dose of the vaccine by 31 March 2021. If the number of new people receiving vaccinations remains the same instead of increasing, the number will reach 86,612,118 in the same time frame. Johnson & Johnson plans to deliver 20 million doses of their vaccine throughout the U.S. in March 2021, adding to the supply. This will have a positive impact on the supply of vaccines, especially since it requires only one dose as opposed to other vaccines which require two. Issues which could have a negative impact on the ability to vaccinate new people include public willingness and supply chain issues. Based on this information, I believe the number of people having received at least one dose of the COVID-19 vaccine in the U.S. as of 31 March 2021 is most likely between 85 and 95 million people, assigning a 28% chance to each 5 million range. I believe the numbers are more likely to exceed my prediction than to fall below it due to the priority placed on vaccination by the federal administration.

According to the CDC Data Tracker, NPR’s COVID-19 Vaccine Tracker, and Bloomberg’s COVID-19 Vaccine Tracker, as of March 6th, around 87.9 million doses have been administered to the American people, making up about 17.3% of the total US population. More than 29.7 million have received two doses, and over 57.3 million have received one dose. There have been 116,355,405 vaccines delivered across the country according to the CDC, and in the past week, 2.16 million doses were administered on average per day. According to the New York Times tracker, the average number of vaccine doses given per day seems to be on an overall upward slope since they began rolling out vaccines in December. Today is March 6th, meaning there are 25 days before the 31st. With around 2.16 million vaccines being administered daily, there will be roughly 53.95 million more vaccines administered by the 31st. Adding this to the number of people who have received one or more doses, roughly 111,309,349 people will have received one or more doses by the end of the month. However, I started thinking that some of these 53.95 million doses will be administered to people getting their second shot, which will not add to the total number of people who have received one or more doses of a COVID-19 vaccine. So, I had to reevaluate and calculate how many people will be receiving their first dose over the next 25 days. According to the New York Times tracker, over the last week, 1,274,759 first doses were administered on average per day. Doing the math, this means that roughly 31.86 million people will receive their first vaccine by the 31st, adding up to a total of 89,227,824 people who will have received one or more vaccines by the end of the month. The newly approved Johnson & Johnson vaccine is not yet recorded in CDC data, so this might lend to more cases recorded over the next month. Given this calculation and the fact that the daily average number of doses is steadily rising every day with the US having the ultimate goal of administering 3 million shots on average per day, I am giving a 0% chance of fewer than 90 million; 5% chance of between 90 million and 95 million inclusive; 40% chance of more the 95 million but fewer than 100 million; 40% chance of between 100 million and 105 million inclusive; 8% chance of more than 105 million but fewer than 110 million; 5% chance of between 110 million and 115 million inclusive; and a 2% chance of more than 115 million people in the U.S. receiving one or more doses of a COVID-19 vaccine by 31 March 2021.

The 'One or more doses' element of the question continues to leave some uncertainty around how to forecast the progress. There are three figures of note: 1) Total doses given 2) Receiving 'One or more doses' 3) Receiving 2nd dose Assume that 1) = 2) + 3) [Thanks to @Anneinak for her feedback !] I'm using a couple of other assumptions on this forecast: -Simplify the term 'One or more doses' to mean people receiving their first dose only, and not including the second dose. These 'One+ dose and the '2nd dose' figures stack up relatively closely to monitor the 'total doses given' so there is strong correlation that we're using the right numbers ! -'Total doses given' figure continues to rise, trending at a increase of about 200K doses per week on over the last 5-6 weeks... steady operational progress -Between 24th January and 15th February, as the vaccination programme got rolling and found a groove, the 'One or more doses' daily figure topped out at a steady 7-day moving average of ~930K 'One or more doses' per day, which likely represents something close to a significant operational limitation give or take 10% either way. -The 'people receiving dose 2' figure continues to rise as more people are 'eligible' which will include a larger proportion of the 'Total Doses given' figure -The weather conditions from mid-February showed a decline in all the three figures, with operational hurdles. The last week of February showed a gargantuan effort by the entire programme to 'catch up for lost time' and 'Total doses given' average over the last 2 weeks of February were similar to 'Total doses given' before the mid-February storm. -Note: the 'Vaccination Trends' tab provides an interesting look at weekly trends, including the 'Sunday slowdown' effect. See https://covid.cdc.gov/covid-data-tracker/#vaccination-trends -I will assume that there will be a continued increase in 'Total doses given', with a growing proportion being '2nd doses'. -A daily moving average for 'One or more' doses of between 910K and 1.1M dose per day will result in between 80-85 M 'One or more' doses given, which I believe is the most likely outcome.
